Data Collection¶

Fo this tutorial I have used the IMDB movies data. The data hold information regarding all the movie that are released all over the world from .

For this tutorial, I will be using Python 3 and the following standard libraries:

  1. Numpy
  2. Pandas
  3. Scikit-Learn - for machine learning
  4. Seaborn - making pretty plots (uses matplotlib)
  5. Plotly - creating the map of New York City
  6. Matplotlib - more pretty plots (also necessary for seaborn)!
  7. StatsModels - generating stats summary for our models

Coulumn heading and the description -¶

  • color: Indicates whether the movie is in color or black and white.
  • director_name: The name of the director of the movie.
  • num_critic_for_reviews: The number of critic reviews for the movie.
  • duration: The duration of the movie in minutes.
  • director_facebook_likes: The number of Facebook likes for the director.
  • actor_3_facebook_likes: The number of Facebook likes for the third actor in the movie.
  • actor_2_name: The name of the second actor in the movie.
  • actor_1_facebook_likes: The number of Facebook likes for the first actor in the movie.
  • gross: The gross earnings of the movie.
  • genres: The genres of the movie (e.g., action, drama, comedy).
  • actor_1_name: The name of the first actor in the movie.
  • movie_title: The title of the movie.
  • num_voted_users: The number of users who voted for the movie on IMDB.
  • cast_total_facebook_likes: The total number of Facebook likes for all actors in the movie.
  • actor_3_name: The name of the third actor in the movie.
  • facenumber_in_poster: The number of faces visible on the movie poster.
  • plot_keywords: Keywords associated with the movie's plot.
  • movie_imdb_link: The IMDB link for the movie.
  • num_user_for_reviews: The number of user reviews for the movie.
  • language: The language of the movie.
  • country: The country where the movie was produced.
  • content_rating: The content rating of the movie (e.g., PG-13, R, G).
  • budget: The budget of the movie.
  • title_year: The year when the movie was released.
  • actor_2_facebook_likes: The number of Facebook likes for the second actor in the movie.
  • imdb_score: The IMDB rating score for the movie.
  • aspect_ratio: The aspect ratio of the movie.
  • movie_facebook_likes: The number of Facebook likes for the movie's Facebook page.

This dataset is the IMDb dataset of movies. It contains 28 variables for 5043 movies spanning across 100 years in 66 countries. There are 2399 unique director names, and thousands of actors/actresses.

The IMDB movie dataset contains 28 variables for 4747 movies from many different countries

# Adding a new logical column 'profitable' indicating if the movie was profitable or not
data1['profitable'] = data1['profit'] > 0

# Calculating p_hat (proportion of profitable movies)
profitable_trues = data1['profitable'].sum()
total_movies = len(data1)
p_hat = profitable_trues / total_movies

p_hat

Hypothesis Testing¶

The Null Hypothesis would be that 50% or less of the movies are profitable.

The Alternative Hypothesis would be that more that 50% of the movies are profitable. We can represent this as:

In [ ]:
import statsmodels.api as sm
from statsmodels.stats.proportion import proportions_ztest

# Add the 'profitable' column
data['profitable'] = np.where(data['Profit'] > 0, True, False)

# Calculate the number of profitable and unprofitable movies
profitable_count = data['profitable'].sum()
total_count = len(data)

# Calculate p_hat
p_hat = profitable_count / total_count

# Set the significance level
alpha = 0.05

# Perform the hypothesis test
z_stat, p_value = proportions_ztest(profitable_count, total_count, value=0.5)

# Evaluate the p-value
if p_value <= alpha:
    print(p_value)
    print(alpha)
    print("Reject the null hypothesis")
else:
    print("Fail to reject the null hypothesis")
